                      <span>2004-08-13</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>The beginning intro the C# is absolutely POINTLESS. The author should have spent more time on providing better examples and discussions of his design patterns.
<br />
<br />Pg 110: "In both cases our events classes contain an instance of the base Events class, which we use to read in the data files."
<br />
<br />Ok, the base Events class he is talking about has been declared as an Abstract class... and he is telling us that our derived classes contain instances of the base Events class? What is he trying to do, provide misinformation? You can't instantiate or have instances of Abstract classes!
<br />
<br />This is an utter waste of $... </span>
                  
              
